on compounds with underlying electronic principles.","why_cuet_level":"It assesses understanding of electronic transitions in coordination chemistry related to ligand effects.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Both statements accurately reflect how ligands affect electronic properties leading to color changes.","B":"Reason is valid but does not fully encompass all aspects influencing color change beyond just d-orbital splitting.","C":"While Assertion is true, the claim about Reason being false overlooks key interactions between ligands and metals.","D":"This option misrepresents both statements by dismissing their validity regarding ligand influence."}},{"q":"Read the statements regarding coordination compounds and choose the correct option: Statement I: Coordination number refers to the total number of ligand atoms bonded to a central metal atom. Statement II: All ligands have a similar ability to stabilize metal ions in solution. Statement III: The type of ligand can significantly affect both stability and reactivity of coordination complexes.","o":["I and III only","I and II only","II and III only","I, II and III"],"a":"A","question_type":"statement_based","concept_id":"chemistry::coordination_compounds","trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["B","C"],"why_not_textbook":"Understanding ligand properties requires knowledge beyond surface-level definitions found in textbooks.","why_cuet_level":"This question evaluates comprehension of ligand behavior in coordination chemistry contexts.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Both statements are correct; coordination number is defined accurately, and ligand type influences complex behavior significantly.","B":"Statement II incorrectly generalizes ligand behavior; different ligands stabilize metals differently based on their properties.","C":"Statement II fails as it doesn't recognize that not all ligands interact with metals similarly or effectively in solutions.","D":"This option incorrectly asserts that all three statements are